                    <desc>
                        <p type="site-data" source="#bibl000299a-1">
                            The <term ref="/place/000299c">Jingangbaozuo Pagoda 金剛寶座塔</term> has two openings 券門 which allow for entry. Being a part of the pagoda, the entrance to the pagoda may have received renovations in 1761 and may have received renovations in 1751 and 1979 when renovations were made to the site overall. In its current form it is brick with a white stone façade (Beijing shi wenwu ju 2008, vol. 1, 256). The door is set into the pagoda under a round arch that frames the top half of the door. The bottom half of the door is framed by vertical sides which continue the lotus blossom protrusions that are present on the rest of the pagoda’s façade. (Beijing shi wenwu ju 2008, vol. 2, 224) (Xu 2010). 
                        </p>
                        <p type="site-data">
                            The rounded arch which frames the door contains many instances of inscribed animal iconography. These include elephants, lions, snakes and horses. These animals are accompanied by nature imagery. The top of the arch is inscribed with humanoid figures accompanied by Buddhist iconography.  
                        </p>
                        <p type="site-data">
                            The interior of the building can be circumambulated and is enterable from doors in the center of the north and south sides. The walkways within the building are topped with rounded arches. The interior area of the walkways contains rounded arch niches for Buddhist iconographic figures. The area before the rounded arch on the interior side of the walkways contains reduplicated bracketing with a slightly overhanging roof in the Yellow River style above. The bracketing and roof both use stone to imitate wood.                            
                        </p>
                    </desc> 
